Dataset Overview and Observations¶

  1. Total Records:

  2. Missing Values:

    • All other columns are complete with no missing values.

  3. Data Types Breakdown:

    • Numerical Columns: 19 columns (int64 / float64).
    • Categorical Columns: 5 columns (object), likely including:
      • Gender, Customer Type, Type of Travel, Class, Satisfaction.

  4. Data Type Anomaly:

    • Flight Distance is of type object but should be numeric.
      • Likely contains non-numeric characters (e.g., spaces, commas, or placeholders) that need cleaning.

  5. Target Column:

    • Satisfaction appears to be the target variable for classification.

  6. Duplicates:

    • No duplicate rows found in the dataset.

  7. Memory Usage:

    • The dataset uses approximately 23.8 MB of memory, which is reasonable for processing.

  8. Potential Outliers:

    • Departure Delay: Max = 1592, 75% = 12, Median = 0 — right-skewed with extreme values.
    • Arrival Delay: Max = 1584, 75% = 13, Median = 0 — heavily skewed with high maximum values.
    • Flight Distance: Should be numeric but is currently an object — likely contains invalid characters or outliers once cleaned.

  • For the columns Flight Distance, Departure Delay, and Arrival Delay, the IQR method was used to detect and handle outliers.
  • The IQR is calculated by finding the 25th percentile (Q1) and the 75th percentile (Q3), then determining the lower bound and upper bound as follows:
    • Lower bound: Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    • Upper bound: Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
  • Values below the lower bound are replaced with the lower bound, and values above the upper bound are replaced with the upper bound, thus capping the outliers.
In [21]:
for i in ["Flight Distance","Departure Delay","Arrival Delay"]:
    Q1 = df[i].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[i].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # Correct lambda without nesting
    df[i] = df[i].apply(lambda x: upper_bound if x > upper_bound else (lower_bound if x < lower_bound else x))


    df[i] = pd.to_numeric(df[i])

Observations from Correlation Matrix¶

  1. Delays are Strongly Related:

    • Departure Delay and Arrival Delay have a very high positive correlation (0.84), indicating that if a flight departs late, it is very likely to arrive late.

  2. In-flight Experience Features are Interconnected:

    • Features like Seat Comfort, Cleanliness, Food and Drink, and In-flight Entertainment show moderate to strong positive correlations with each other, suggesting that better in-flight experience tends to be consistently rated across multiple aspects.

  3. Online Services are Interrelated:

    • Ease of Online Booking, Online Boarding, and In-flight Wifi Service are positively correlated, reflecting a pattern that customers who use or like one online service often rate others positively too.

  4. Flight Distance Has Weak Correlation:

    • Flight Distance does not show strong correlation with delays or service quality features, suggesting it might be independent of perceived service or punctuality.

  5. Age Has Weak to Moderate Correlation:

    • Age has weak to moderate positive correlation with Online Boarding and Seat Comfort, which might suggest older passengers tend to rate some services slightly higher.

  6. Gate Location is Largely Unrelated:

    • Gate Location shows minimal or near-zero correlation with most other features, implying it's perceived independently by passengers.

  • Dropped the Departure Delay column: The column Departure Delay is removed from the numerical feature set (Num) to reduce multicollinearity, as it is highly correlated with Arrival Delay. This helps improve model performance by preventing redundancy.

  • Reduced dimensionality: By removing Departure Delay, the dimensionality of the dataset is reduced, simplifying the model and improving interpretability without losing significant information, as Arrival Delay is retained.

Observations¶

  • Neutral or Dissatisfied by Age: The distribution of neutral or dissatisfied customers is concentrated mostly between the ages of 20 to 60 years.
  • Neutral or Dissatisfied by Flight Distance: The distribution shows that most neutral or dissatisfied customers have flight distances ranging from 0 to around 2000 miles.
  • Neutral or Dissatisfied by Arrival Delay: The majority of neutral or dissatisfied customers experience arrival delays between 0 to 15 minutes, with a sudden spike observed between 30 to 35 minutes.

Key Insights:¶

  • Age and Satisfaction:
    Most satisfied and neutral/dissatisfied customers are concentrated between the ages of 20 to 60 years, indicating this age group is more sensitive to service quality and delays.

  • Flight Distance and Satisfaction:
    Satisfied customers are spread across a broader range of flight distances (up to 4000 miles), while neutral/dissatisfied customers are primarily concentrated in the 0 to 2000-mile range, highlighting that longer flights tend to have higher satisfaction levels.

  • Arrival Delay and Satisfaction:
    Satisfied customers generally experience shorter arrival delays (0 to 10 minutes), while neutral or dissatisfied customers show a significant spike in dissatisfaction for delays between 30 to 35 minutes, suggesting that delays beyond 15 minutes severely impact satisfaction.

  • Service Quality and Satisfaction:
    High satisfaction is strongly linked to superior service quality (e.g., on-board service, seat comfort) and convenience (e.g., online booking and boarding), emphasizing the importance of efficient services.

  • Dissatisfaction and Delays:
    Arrival delays between 0 to 15 minutes are the most common cause of dissatisfaction, but delays beyond 30 minutes lead to a sharp rise in complaints, suggesting critical time thresholds for customer experience.

  • Service Quality & Convenience: High satisfaction correlates with better service quality (e.g., on-board service, seat comfort) and convenience (e.g., online booking, online boarding).

  • Ratings Impact: Low ratings (1 & 2) indicate areas for improvement, especially in wifi, food/drink, and baggage handling.

  • Customer & Demographic Trends: Returning customers and business travelers tend to be more dissatisfied, possibly due to higher expectations.

  • Gender Differences: Although satisfaction is similar, females report more dissatisfaction, indicating service issues that may affect them more. like this

  • Class:Business Class passengers report the highest satisfaction, whereas Economy Class passengers show the most dissatisfaction, highlighting a clear link between travel class and customer satisfaction.

Model Building¶

  • I am Using all Above Models For Finding Suitable And Best Model
Model Type Comment
Logistic Regression Linear Simple and interpretable. Performs well on linearly separable data.
Decision Tree Tree-Based Easy to understand; can overfit without proper pruning.
Random Forest Ensemble (Bagging) Combines multiple trees to reduce overfitting and improve performance.
Gradient Boosting Boosting Sequentially improves errors. Performs well on complex data.
AdaBoost Boosting Focuses on correcting previous errors. Sensitive to noisy data.
SVC Kernel-Based Effective in high-dimensional spaces. Requires scaling and tuning.
KNN Distance-Based Predicts using closest data points. Needs scaling; slower on big data.
Naive Bayes Probabilistic Very fast and simple. Assumes feature independence.

Observations¶

Bias: Low¶

  • Because the model is achieving high accuracy on both training and test data.
  • If bias were high, it would perform poorly on both.

Variance: Low¶

  • The difference between Train Accuracy (1.0%) and Test Accuracy (0.96%) is very small, indicating low variance.
  • High variance would show a large gap (e.g., 99% train, 70% test).

Train Accuracy: 1.0%¶

  • Directly measured — shows model fits training data well. Test Accuracy: 0.96%
  • Also measured — confirms model generalizes well to unseen data.

Overfitting: Not significant (Train ≈ Test)¶

  • Since train and test accuracies are very close, overfitting is not a concern here.

Underfitting: Not present¶

  • High training accuracy means the model is capturing the data patterns well. Underfitting would show low accuracy on both train and test.

Generalization: Good¶

  • High and close train/test accuracy = model generalizes well. -This means it should perform similarly on new, real-world da

  • Overall, the confusion matrix supports the strong metrics in the classification report (96% accuracy, high precision/recall).

ROC Curve and AUC Score¶

In [123]:
y_true = y_test
y_pred_proba = model.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1]

fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_true, y_pred_proba)


roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)



plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='b', lw=2, label='ROC curve (AUC = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='gray', linestyle='--')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.show()
  • ROC Curve: Visualizes the performance of a binary classifier by plotting the True Positive Rate (TPR) against the False Positive Rate (FPR) at various threshold settings.
  • Axes:
    • Y-axis: True Positive Rate (TPR) or Sensitivity (Correctly identified positives / Total actual positives). Higher is better.
    • X-axis: False Positive Rate (FPR) (Incorrectly identified positives / Total actual negatives). Lower is better.
  • Ideal Curve: A good model's ROC curve bends sharply towards the top-left corner (TPR=1, FPR=0).
  • Baseline: The dashed diagonal line represents a random classifier (AUC = 0.5). A model should perform above this line.
  • AUC (Area Under the Curve): A single metric summarizing performance across all thresholds.
    • Ranges from 0 (worst) to 1 (perfect).
    • 0.5 indicates random performance.
  • This Specific Curve:
    • Shows excellent performance as the curve is very close to the top-left corner.
    • Has an AUC of 0.99, indicating outstanding ability to distinguish between the positive and negative classes.
